An 'oasis' signifies a refugium of safety, recovery, relaxation, fertility, and 
productivity in an inhospitable desert, a sweet spot in a barren landscape where 
life-giving water spills forth from the Earth. Remarkable mythological 
congruencies exist across dryland cultures worldwide where oases or 'arid-land 
springs' occur. In many places they also provide specialised habitats for an 
extraordinary array of endemic organisms. To inform their management, and 
maintain their integrity, it is essential to understand the hydrogeology of 
aquifers and springs. Gravity-fed vs artesian aquifers; actively recharged vs 
fossil aquifers, and sources of geothermal activity are important concepts 
presented here. There consequences for oases of sustainable and unsustainable 
groundwater extraction, and other examples of effective conservation management. 
Oases are archetypes for human consciousness, habitats that deserve protection 
and conservation, and a lingua franca for multicultural values and scientific 
exchange. We represent an international Fellowship of the Spring seeking to 
encompass and facilitate the stewardship of oases and aquifers through improved 
knowledge, outreach, and governance.

